[1]
Date: 8 Sep 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Strait Times
<http://www.straitstimes.asia1.com/latest/story/0,4390,208815,00.html?>

Patient at SGH tests positive for Sars virus
-----------------------
A patient at the Singapore General Hospital tested positive for the SARS
virus on Monday, triggering concern that the respiratory disease may have
resurfaced here.
Hospital staff asked visitors to leave wards 74 and 78 in the late afternoon.
The Straits Times learnt that more tests were done on the Singaporean man
to confirm if the preliminary test result was correct, or if it was a false
positive.
He worked in a virology laboratory at Kent Ridge, but apparently was not
working with the SARS virus.
A Health Ministry spokesman said that Acting Health Minister Khaw Boon Wan
will hold a press conference on Tuesday once the results are known.
She said that the man was sent to Tan Tock Seng Hospital on Monday.
The SGH has started tracing everyone who may have been in contact with him,
including those who were at the accident and emergency department when he
went there last week with a fever.
It is believed that the man, who has not been to China or Hong Kong
recently, was at the A&E [emergency] department for 2 hours.
[By Salma Khalik]
